HTML Entities and Code Tag
1. HTML Entities

HTML entities are used to display reserved characters or symbols that cannot be typed directly in HTML.

Why are Entities Needed?

Some characters have special meaning in HTML:

< and > are used for tags
& is used for entities

To display them as text, we use HTML entities.

Syntax
&entity_name;

or

&#entity_number;
Common HTML Entities
Character	Entity Name	Entity Number
<	&lt;	&#60;
>	&gt;	&#62;
&	&amp;	&#38;
"	&quot;	&#34;
'	&apos;	&#39;
Space	&nbsp;	&#160;
Example
<p>This is &lt;b&gt;bold&lt;/b&gt; text</p>
Output

This is <b>bold</b> text

Features
Prevents browser from interpreting special characters
Used for symbols and formatting
Ensures correct display of content
2. <code> Tag in HTML

The <code> tag is used to display programming code in a webpage.

Syntax
<code>your code here</code>
Example
<p>Example of code: <code>int x = 10;</code></p>
Features
Displays text in monospace font
Used for inline code snippets
Improves readability of technical content
Multiline Code (with <pre> tag)

To preserve spacing and line breaks, use <pre> with <code>.

<pre>
<code>
#include &lt;iostream&gt;
using namespace std;

int main() {
    cout &lt;&lt; "Hello";
}
</code>
</pre>
